I have a two head display on a Sun Ultra 60 with two gfx cards. I like
to run two fvwm2 sessions, one on each screen.

I start fvwm2 from my ~/.xinitrc like this:

	fvwm2 -cmd "FvwmM4 -DSHORT_HOST=$HOSTNAME $HOME/.fvwm2/fvwm2rc"

where $HOSTNAME is something like foo instead of foo.stanford.edu. I know
that FvwmM4 defines HOSTNAME, but it always turns out to be
foo.stanford.edu
instead of just foo.

Then I have a menu item that Restarts fvwm2. In 2.0.46 and 2.2.4, I would
just say:

	Restart fvwm2

and everything would work.

Now, however, nothing works. I've read all the info on the Restart option
with 2.4.3 and I've tried all kinds of experimentation with --pass-args,
-s and -replace but nothing seems to work. I think it has to do with the
fact that when fvwm2 originally starts, it sucessfully deals with
the fact that I have two screens. But when I try to restart, my most
frequent error message is that FVWM has detected another ICCCCCCM2.0
compliant WM and I should try the -replace flag.

The problem is that I can't just say "Restart" because I need to add the
-replace flag, but I can't just say Restart fvwm2 -replace because then
I'd lose the initial arguments. Notice that I also can't just copy the 
contents of .xinitrc into the Restart command because each time through,
FvwmM4 will perform replacement (making -DSHORT_HOST literally into -Dfoo)

I *think* what I need is for yet another form of the Restart command
that allows me to specify --pass-args but also supply new ones.

Perhaps I'm way out to sea here, but if anyone has any idea what is going
on, it would be really appreciated.

Thanks,

Jeff


